The paper deals with the relationship between two models of distributed computing, the Iterated Immediate Snapshot model (IIS) and the Atomic-Snapshot memory model (AS). This falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also involves topological reasoning, which suggests a possible connection to Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO). Additionally, the paper discusses algorithms and simulations, which are relevant to Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Programming Languages (cs.PL). Finally, the paper deals with the task computability power of the models, which could be related to Systems and Control (cs.SY).
